Aggregation example

RW Hass

2025-02-11

What is aggregation?

Aggregation loosely refers to summarizing over a set of lower level cases in a hierarchically nested data structure. For example, lets say we have information about patients, and about the clinics theyre seen in, or their doctors.

We may want to test hypotheses about how characteristics of a doctor relate to patient outcomes. Using ordinary least squares, we can either leave the data at the patient level or aggregate the patients outcomes to get doctor-level patient outcomes (i.e., mean satisfaction per doctor).

Today well explore how the choice of modeling effects inferences. Specifically, the standard errors used to compute confidence intervals and \(p\)-values.

  • Note: this vignette relies on jtools, ggplot2 and lme4 and part 2 was adapted from this post by Francis Huang

Simpsons paradox

A related issue is Simpsons paradox. The issue does not just affect clustered data, but is more general in that it addresses the fact that when we ignore grouping structures in data we can come to erroneous conclusions.

To illustrate, heres a hypothetical data set constructed specifically for this example (from the Snijders and Bosker book) with \(J = 5\) clusters, each with an \(n = 2\) for an overall \(N = 10\)

##    Participant Cluster Outcome Predictor
## 1            1       1       5         1
## 2            2       1       7         3
## 3            3       2       4         2
## 4            4       2       6         4
## 5            5       3       3         3
## 6            6       3       5         5
## 7            7       4       2         4
## 8            8       4       4         6
## 9            9       5       1         5
## 10          10       5       3         7

Lets fit a linear model for the Outcome ignoring the Cluster variable and plot the result:

If we werent aware of the different clusters, we might accept that the fit is poor, but still see that theres a negative linear association between the Predictor and the Outcome

The between-groups effect

Lets aggregate up, creating a new data set with \(N = 5\) representing the relationship between the mean predictor and mean outcome across the groups:

## unreliable

(Intercept) 8.00 0.00 35704860762310480.00 0.00
Predictor -1.00 0.00 -18935361874763416.00 0.00
Standard errors: OLS

Now we have a perfect fit, and its still negative. Note, we have no standard errors here, but thats fine. Well see more on that later.

The final option would be to simply look within each group, and somehow summarize over that. For each group, it turns out the following regression equation holds perfectly:

\[ Y_{ij} = \bar{Y}_{.j} + 1.00(X_{ij} - \bar{X}_{.j}) + r_{ij} \]

That is, within each group, the relationship between predictor and outcome is positive, as shown below!

These data were actually generated using a multilevel model, but are quite unrealistic. Lets see what a more realistic, though synthetic example might look like.

Example 2

Though Simpsons paradox is not always common, the more important point not seen in the above is that the way you aggregate, or dont, also affects standard errors, so it will effect the nature of the inferences, even if the signs dont change in and between clusters.

As a more realistic demonstration, Ive simulated a dataset with equal cluster sizes (\(N_{j} = 30\)), and \(J = 20\) clusters. The variables are:

  1. y a numeric outcome variable ranging from about \(-12\) to about \(15\) with \(\bar{X} = 0.94\). Lets imagine this is a rescaled patient-reported outcome measure from a pain scale.
  2. l1 a patient-level (level-1) predictor. It is also numeric, with \(\bar{X} = 0.01\), \(\text{SD} = 1.02\) think of this as a noisy measure of anxiety
  3. l2 a hospital-level effect corresponding to a standardized measure of pain management efficiency. Well wait on reporting its characteristics
set.seed(1234) #for reproducability
nG <- 20 #number of groups
nJ <- 30 #cluster size
W1 <- .2 #level 2 coeff
X1 <- 0.75 #level 1 coeff
intcep <- 0.34

tmp2 <- rnorm(nG, mean = 0, sd = 3) #generate 20 random numbers, m = 0, sd = 1
l2 <- rep(tmp2, each = nJ) #all units in l2 have the same value
group <- gl(nG, k = nJ) #creating cluster variable
tmp2 <- rnorm(nG) #error term for level 2
err2 <- rep(tmp2, each = nJ) #all units in l2 have the same value

l1 <- rnorm(nG * nJ) #total sample size is nG * nJ
err1 <- rnorm(nG * nJ, sd = 4) #level 1 

#putting it all together
y <- intcep + W1 * l2 + X1 * l1 + err2 + err1
dat <- data.frame(y, group, l2, err2,l1, err1)

Visualize

Lets first have a look at the overall relationship between anxiety (l1) and pain (\(Y\))

Unclustered / dis-aggregated model

Lets fit linear model for the total regression, ignoring all the clusters, and including the level 2 (l2) variable.

unclustered <- lm(y ~ l1 + l2, data = dat)

Multilevel Model

Now lets have a look at the scatterplot for the level-1 variable again, but this time, well see how the patient-level pain-anxiety relationship might vary between the groups

So theres at least 1 group where the anxiety-pain relationship is flatter than the others. Well now fit a linear mixed-effects regression to handle this multilevel nested structure. Note that the standard errors will be different as well as the output.

First, well fit what well learn to call the unconditional model. This seems boring, but the idea is that we dont specify anything but the random-effects for group. The output gives us the estimate of the intraclass correlation (ICC), as well as how much the group intercepts are varying

mm_mod <- lmer(y ~ (1 | group), dat)
summ(mm_mod)

Now well fit what well learn to call the random-effects ANCOVA where we allow for the intercepts to vary across groups, as well as the effect of l1. Well get a residual ICC as well as information about the variation of these effects.

Also notice the strange \(df\) values. Well have more to say about that in coming weeks.

mm_mod1 <- lmer(y ~ l1 + l2 + (l1| group), data = dat)

Notice that the regression coefficients are nearly identical, but that the standard errors are , especially for l2 the hospital-level variable. Also notice how the p-values changed among the models. Well learn more about that over the next few weeks.

Summary

  1. When data are naturally nested, ignoring that structure and analyzing the data as if no grouping structure produces biased standard errors (usually too small).
  2. Aggregating up may make it look like the overall fit is good (\(R^{2}\)) but we lose power, and we can no longer make inferences about individuals (SEs are larger due to smaller sample size at group level)
  3. Using random effects, we can use a multilevel model to parse out the variation within and between groups to get a less biased view of whats going on
  4. There are other options to adjust SEs, but not when we are interested in level-2 effects
